might not be afforded?

04:22.433 --> 04:27.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They're saying, well, maybe the
NCAA can consider that an extra
benefit, and, in that sense,

04:29.100 --> 04:31.066 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
it could come in and take
some enforcement action.

04:31.066 --> 04:35.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: The issue of sexual
assaults on - - sexual violence
on college campuses has

04:35.733 --> 04:38.466 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
gotten a lot of discussion.

04:38.466 --> 04:43.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Talk about sort of the bigger
issue here of how colleges
even outside athletic programs

04:45.233 --> 04:46.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
are dealing with that.

04:46.633 --> 04:49.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
PAULA LAVIGNE: It
is a huge issue.

04:49.466 --> 04:54.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There's been statistics that
have been backed up by numerous
research that one in five women

04:56.366 --> 05:00.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
will experience some
sort of type of sexual
assault while in college.

05:00.300 --> 05:04.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And right now, there's more than
200 colleges and universities
under investigation by the

05:04.666 --> 05:07.266 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
U.S. Department of Education.

05:07.266 --> 05:12.000 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
However, this is a perfect
time to be talking about
this, because a lot of
the federal government's

05:13.966 --> 05:17.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
civil rights enforcement
actions are being called into
question right now, and one of

05:18.166 --> 05:20.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
those deals specifically
with Title IX.

05:20.566 --> 05:25.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And Title IX is the venue that
the U.S. Department of Education
uses to enforce how colleges

05:28.233 --> 05:31.200 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and universities are
addressing sexual violence.

05:31.200 --> 05:36.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And there are a lot of people
who are saying schools shouldn't
be involved in what is seen

05:37.133 --> 05:39.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
as a criminal matter.

05:39.133 --> 05:43.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And a problem with that is that
that's pretty short-sighted,
because Title IX does a lot

05:46.433 --> 05:50.233 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
more in addressing
sexual violence than just
determining whether or
not an alleged perpetrator

05:51.100 --> 05:53.233 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
is responsible for the act.

05:53.233 --> 05:57.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
I mean, one of the --
you mentioned the case
involving Tevin Elliot.

05:57.500 --> 06:02.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The young woman in that
case, I mean, she saw her
accused perpetrator convicted.

06:04.500 --> 06:08.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
However, her biggest issue was
the fact that she didn't get
the counseling services, she

06:09.933 --> 06:12.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
didn't get the
academic services.

06:12.000 --> 06:14.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
She was basically sort
of left floundering.

06:14.533 --> 06:19.166 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She ends up dropping out,
doesn't get to pursue
her dream, and has to
transfer and move back

06:19.633 --> 06:21.700 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
home.

06:21.700 --> 06:24.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There is nothing in the criminal
justice system that provides
that sort of remedy, and that's

06:24.300 --> 06:26.366 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
what Title IX is designed to do.

06:26.366 --> 06:31.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
It's designed to force
these schools to address
specific cases of
sexual violence, in part

06:32.766 --> 06:34.900 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to determine whether or
not someone is responsible.

06:34.900 --> 06:39.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But the bigger part, the part
that's often ignored, is by
providing a safe campus for

06:41.866 --> 06:45.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
these women to attend, providing
counseling services if they
need them, providing academic

06:45.100 --> 06:48.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
services to make them
whole again, so they can
continue their education.

06:48.933 --> 06:52.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JOHN YANG: Paula Lavigne
of ESPN, thanks so
much for joining us.

